1
00:01:08,664 --> 00:01:10,621
Bernard. Minister not in yet?

2
00:01:10,784 --> 00:01:12,695
He's in his office,
having a meeting.

3
00:01:12,864 --> 00:01:14,092
What about?

4
00:01:14,264 --> 00:01:15,936
Nothing very important.

5
00:01:16,104 --> 00:01:17,298
I see.

6
00:01:17,464 --> 00:01:20,262
And whatwas that meeting
in there yesterday?

7
00:01:20,464 --> 00:01:23,103
He was just reviewing
procedures for briefing him

8
00:01:23,264 --> 00:01:25,573
on answers
to Parliamentary questions.

9
00:01:26,224 --> 00:01:30,615
But there were Principals present
and other assorted underlings.

10
00:01:30,904 --> 00:01:34,943
Just the ones who supply him
with the information, actually.

11
00:01:35,104 --> 00:01:37,823
Bernard, this has to be stopped
at once.

12
00:01:37,984 --> 00:01:38,984
Why?

13
00:01:39,144 --> 00:01:42,739
Lfhe talks to the underlings,
he may learn things we don't know.

14
00:01:44,144 --> 00:01:48,057
- Ourposition could be undermined.
- If it increases ourknowledge...

15
00:01:48,224 --> 00:01:51,534
It is folly if it's at the expense
of your authority.

16
00:01:51,704 --> 00:01:52,704
Why?

17
00:01:53,504 --> 00:01:55,620
Bernard, please stop saying why.

18
00:01:55,864 --> 00:01:56,864
Why?

19
00:01:58,584 --> 00:02:01,144
I mean, could you develop
that point please?

20
00:02:02,944 --> 00:02:06,095
Would you say that the Minister
is starting to run the Department?

21
00:02:06,504 --> 00:02:09,177
Yes, things are going pretty well,
actually.

22
00:02:09,344 --> 00:02:12,700
No, when a Ministeractually
starts to run his Department

23
00:02:12,864 --> 00:02:14,820
things are not going pretty well.

24
00:02:14,984 --> 00:02:16,861
They are actually
going prettybadly.

25
00:02:17,024 --> 00:02:19,902
But actually... er... I mean, in fact,

26
00:02:20,064 --> 00:02:22,658
isn't it the Minister's job
to run the Department?

27
00:02:22,824 --> 00:02:24,462
No, Bernard, it is ourjob.

28
00:02:24,784 --> 00:02:26,581
Orto be more precise,
it is my job,

29
00:02:26,744 --> 00:02:29,702
forwhich I've had 25 years
experience and training.

30
00:02:29,864 --> 00:02:33,379
Don't you realise whatwould
happen if the Ministerruns it?

31
00:02:33,544 --> 00:02:34,544
No, what?

32
00:02:34,704 --> 00:02:36,934
First, there would be chaos,
naturally.

33
00:02:37,104 --> 00:02:39,664
And second,
which is much more serious,

34
00:02:39,824 --> 00:02:41,655
there would be innovations.

35
00:02:41,824 --> 00:02:43,098
Changes, Bernard.

36
00:02:43,264 --> 00:02:45,141
Public debate.
Outside scrutiny.

37
00:02:45,384 --> 00:02:46,817
Is that what you want?

38
00:02:48,384 --> 00:02:51,456
Good heavens, no.
But what should he do then?

39
00:02:51,904 --> 00:02:54,134
A Ministerhas three functions.

40
00:02:54,304 --> 00:02:55,942
First, as an advocate,

41
00:02:56,104 --> 00:02:58,777
making the Department's actions
seem plausible

42
00:02:58,944 --> 00:03:02,141
to Parliament and public,
he is ourpublic relations man.

43
00:03:02,384 --> 00:03:04,818
Second, he is ourman
in Westminster,

44
00:03:04,984 --> 00:03:08,021
steering our legislation
through Parliament.

45
00:03:08,184 --> 00:03:10,618
And third, he is ourbreadwinner.

46
00:03:11,184 --> 00:03:13,857
He has to fight in Cabinet
forthe money we need

47
00:03:14,024 --> 00:03:15,662
to run our Department.

48
00:03:16,344 --> 00:03:19,302
But, he is not here to review
departmental procedures

49
00:03:19,464 --> 00:03:21,534
with Principals
and Assistant Secretaries.

50
00:03:21,704 --> 00:03:24,172
- But ifhe's go the time.
- Why has he got the time?

51
00:03:24,344 --> 00:03:27,017
He shouldn't.
That's yourfault, Bernard!

52
00:03:27,264 --> 00:03:29,653
You must ensure
he hasn't got the time.

53
00:03:30,304 --> 00:03:32,022
Create activity, Bernard!

54
00:03:32,224 --> 00:03:34,692
He should be making
speeches, visits.

55
00:03:34,864 --> 00:03:36,900
We need deputations,
junkets abroad,

56
00:03:37,064 --> 00:03:40,943
mountains of red boxes, we need
crises, emergencies, panics!

57
00:03:41,344 --> 00:03:43,858
- Pull yourself together, Bernard.
- Yes, but...

58
00:03:44,024 --> 00:03:46,697
- You leave spaces in his diary?
- No, he makes those.

59
00:03:46,864 --> 00:03:48,616
- Fill them up.
- He won't let me.

60
00:03:48,784 --> 00:03:50,456
Don't ask him. Do it.

61
00:03:51,064 --> 00:03:54,693
Make sure he spends more time
where he can't do any damage.

62
00:03:54,864 --> 00:03:58,493
- But where?
- The House of Commons, for instance.

63
00:03:59,464 --> 00:04:02,456
I really do try my best.
There's a deputation in there.

64
00:04:02,624 --> 00:04:04,774
What is it about, Bernard?

65
00:04:04,944 --> 00:04:09,335
Something completely trivial,
preserving badgers in Warwickshire.

66
00:04:10,704 --> 00:04:12,535
Well done, Bernard.

67
00:04:13,584 --> 00:04:16,815
Why didn't you tell me this
when I asked you before?

68
00:04:17,184 --> 00:04:19,937
Actually, I thought
itwas rathertrivial.

69
00:04:20,104 --> 00:04:23,016
I didn't think
you would approve, actually.

70
00:04:23,184 --> 00:04:24,936
Bernard.

71
00:04:26,104 --> 00:04:29,858
I'll try and find some more
threatened species then, shall I?

72
00:04:30,024 --> 00:04:32,333
You may not have to look veryfar.

73
00:04:32,544 --> 00:04:36,378
Secretaries who can't occupy their
Ministers are a threatened species,

74
00:04:39,264 --> 00:04:40,458
actually.

75
00:04:42,664 --> 00:04:46,623
We have a sacred trust
to preserve ournatural heritage.

76
00:04:46,784 --> 00:04:50,060
That's what this new legislation
is designed to ensure.

77
00:04:50,224 --> 00:04:53,614
As I said in the House,
the system simply isn'tworking.

78
00:04:53,784 --> 00:04:55,297
It's a hotch- potch.

79
00:04:55,504 --> 00:04:57,734
Local authorities,
tourist authorities,

80
00:04:57,904 --> 00:05:01,180
national parks,
countryside commision, C. P. R. E.

81
00:05:01,344 --> 00:05:03,653
Nobody knows where they are,
nothing gets done.

82
00:05:03,824 --> 00:05:05,894
They're all back biting
and buck passing.

83
00:05:06,064 --> 00:05:07,736
You know
what committees are like.

84
00:05:07,904 --> 00:05:09,337
We are a committee.

85
00:05:09,544 --> 00:05:13,583
Yes. I didn't mean
yoursort of committee.

86
00:05:13,744 --> 00:05:17,737
But this new legislation is
designed to create clearauthority,

87
00:05:17,904 --> 00:05:20,372
and save a great deal
of public money.

88
00:05:20,544 --> 00:05:24,332
- You ought to welcome it.
- But what about Hayward's Spinney?

89
00:05:24,504 --> 00:05:28,417
Afew very small areas will lose
theirspecially protected status,

90
00:05:28,584 --> 00:05:31,098
because it isn't economical
any longer,

91
00:05:31,264 --> 00:05:33,334
to maintain them
as they ought to.

92
00:05:33,504 --> 00:05:36,302
Hayward's Spinney is
a vital part of ourheritage.

93
00:05:36,464 --> 00:05:38,853
The badgers have dwelt there
forgenerations.

94
00:05:39,024 --> 00:05:42,380
- Can you be sure of that?
- It said so in The Guardian.

95
00:05:42,544 --> 00:05:43,693
Ah, well...

96
00:05:45,664 --> 00:05:49,373
Actually it says that the badgers
have dwelt there forgenerations!

97
00:05:51,864 --> 00:05:53,456
Howwould you feel if you had

98
00:05:53,624 --> 00:05:56,058
a lot of office blocks
built overyourgarden

99
00:05:56,224 --> 00:05:57,816
by a lot of giant badgers?

100
00:05:57,984 --> 00:06:00,544
But a lot of office blocks...
giant badgers?

101
00:06:01,624 --> 00:06:04,218
There's nothing special
about man, Mr. Hacker.

102
00:06:04,384 --> 00:06:07,296
We're not above nature.
We're all a part of it.

103
00:06:07,464 --> 00:06:09,341
Men are animals too, you know.

104
00:06:09,504 --> 00:06:12,416
Yes, I've just come from
the House of Commons.

105
00:06:13,144 --> 00:06:16,420
Sorry, Minister, you are due
foryournext appoinment.

106
00:06:16,584 --> 00:06:17,858
Oh, what a pity.

107
00:06:18,024 --> 00:06:21,061
Thank you forputting
yourcase so persuasively.

108
00:06:21,224 --> 00:06:22,657
It's been a pleasure.

109
00:06:22,824 --> 00:06:25,099
Left at the corridor
and down the stairs.

110
00:06:26,064 --> 00:06:28,134
But whatwill you do about it?

111
00:06:28,304 --> 00:06:31,421
All views will be taken
into consideration.

112
00:06:31,624 --> 00:06:33,774
Now if you'll excuse me...

113
00:06:37,864 --> 00:06:40,173
Very polished performance.
Gracious.

114
00:06:40,344 --> 00:06:42,062
And said nothing.
Very professional.

115
00:06:42,224 --> 00:06:44,533
- Why wasn't I warned?
- About what?

116
00:06:44,704 --> 00:06:46,581
That unifying the administration

117
00:06:46,744 --> 00:06:50,054
would remove protected status
from this beaverwhatsit?

118
00:06:50,224 --> 00:06:53,455
Badgercolony. Hayward's
Spinney, East Warwickshire.

119
00:06:53,624 --> 00:06:55,421
Somebody
must have know about it.

120
00:06:55,584 --> 00:06:57,336
If somebody did happen to know,

121
00:06:57,504 --> 00:07:00,860
they wouldn't necessarily know
that you wanted to know

122
00:07:01,024 --> 00:07:03,663
what they happened to know,
in case...

123
00:07:03,904 --> 00:07:06,623
- Ah! Sir Humphrey!
- Humphrey!

124
00:07:06,944 --> 00:07:08,263
Good morning, Minister.

125
00:07:08,424 --> 00:07:11,734
Is it yourjob to help Ministers
make fools of themselves?

126
00:07:11,904 --> 00:07:14,020
I have nevermet one
that needed any help.

127
00:07:15,984 --> 00:07:17,542
No, it is the last thing...

128
00:07:17,704 --> 00:07:21,743
Why did you encourage me to say
that unifying the administration

129
00:07:21,904 --> 00:07:25,340
meant no loss of amenity,
when I've signed a death warrant

130
00:07:25,504 --> 00:07:27,142
fora whole army ofbeavers?

131
00:07:27,304 --> 00:07:28,862
- Badgers, Minister.
- What?

132
00:07:29,024 --> 00:07:30,696
Beavers would have a navy.

133
00:07:33,264 --> 00:07:36,495
- Why did you let me do it?
- I did not encourage you to say that.

134
00:07:36,664 --> 00:07:38,814
You did!
The Department prepared this.

135
00:07:39,024 --> 00:07:41,538
- "No loss of amenity", it says.
- No.

136
00:07:41,704 --> 00:07:44,776
- "No significant loss of amenity".
- Same thing.

137
00:07:44,944 --> 00:07:47,014
There's all the difference
in the world.

138
00:07:47,184 --> 00:07:50,176
Almost anything can be attacked
as a "loss of amenity",

139
00:07:50,344 --> 00:07:53,780
and be defended as
"not a significant loss of amenity".

140
00:07:53,944 --> 00:07:57,175
One should appreciate
the significance of"significant".

141
00:07:57,464 --> 00:07:59,102
Well, be that as it may,

142
00:07:59,264 --> 00:08:01,380
any publicity would be
very damaging.

143
00:08:01,544 --> 00:08:02,977
Oh, I think not.

144
00:08:03,144 --> 00:08:05,704
But if there is a loss of amenity...

145
00:08:05,864 --> 00:08:08,253
If you'd approve this release,
you would see

146
00:08:08,424 --> 00:08:10,733
that it does counter
all theirarguments.

147
00:08:10,904 --> 00:08:14,658
It points out that the spinney
is deregistered, not threatened.

148
00:08:14,824 --> 00:08:17,941
Badgers are very plentiful
all overWarwickshire.

149
00:08:18,104 --> 00:08:20,060
And it points out the connection

150
00:08:20,224 --> 00:08:22,533
between Badgers
and brucellosis.

151
00:08:22,864 --> 00:08:26,493
"Cannot be regarded
as a significant loss of amenity".

152
00:08:27,104 --> 00:08:29,459
So this might not get
into the National Press?

153
00:08:29,624 --> 00:08:33,333
Afew lines on The Guardian.
Nothing to worry about.

154
00:08:34,024 --> 00:08:36,333
Only the urban middle class
worry about

155
00:08:36,504 --> 00:08:40,941
the preservation of the countryside,
because they don't live in it.

156
00:08:41,864 --> 00:08:44,059
- Would that be all, Minister?
- Yes!

157
00:08:44,224 --> 00:08:45,896
No, this may well blow over,

158
00:08:46,064 --> 00:08:48,498
but it doesn't answer
my basic question.

159
00:08:48,664 --> 00:08:51,861
- Which was?
- Why wasn't I told about it?

160
00:08:52,024 --> 00:08:56,336
There are those who have argued
and indeed cogently

161
00:08:56,504 --> 00:08:59,177
that on occasion
there are some things

162
00:08:59,344 --> 00:09:01,778
it is betterfora Minister
not to know.

163
00:09:01,944 --> 00:09:03,502
What are you talking about?

164
00:09:03,664 --> 00:09:05,973
Minister, youranswers
in the House

165
00:09:06,144 --> 00:09:08,374
and at the Press Conference
were superb.

166
00:09:08,544 --> 00:09:11,217
You were convincing.
The critics were silenced.

167
00:09:11,384 --> 00:09:14,182
But could you have spoken
with the same authority

168
00:09:14,344 --> 00:09:18,098
if the ecological pressure group
had been badgering you?

169
00:09:18,864 --> 00:09:22,220
But I have a right to know!
I am the people's representative!

170
00:09:22,384 --> 00:09:25,456
What right have you got
to withhold this information?

171
00:09:25,624 --> 00:09:29,253
- It's in yourown best interests.
- What do you mean?

172
00:09:29,424 --> 00:09:32,143
It's outrageous!
It must not occuragain.

173
00:09:32,464 --> 00:09:35,262
I've a plan forthe reorganising
of this Department

174
00:09:35,424 --> 00:09:37,380
which would ensure
that it doesn't.

175
00:09:37,704 --> 00:09:39,296
- Indeed?
- Yes, indeed.

176
00:09:39,464 --> 00:09:41,022
If I had one UnderSecretary

177
00:09:41,184 --> 00:09:43,937
and two Assistant Secretaries
reporting to me...

178
00:09:44,104 --> 00:09:46,937
- Minister. Please!
- Let me tell you my plan.

179
00:09:47,104 --> 00:09:48,662
The plan is immaterial.

180
00:09:48,824 --> 00:09:51,702
Minister, I have
something to say to you

181
00:09:51,864 --> 00:09:53,661
which you may not
like to hear.

182
00:09:54,104 --> 00:09:56,538
Why should today be
any different?

183
00:09:57,944 --> 00:10:03,143
Minister, the traditional allocation
of executive responsabilities

184
00:10:03,304 --> 00:10:06,023
has always been so determined
as to liberate

185
00:10:06,184 --> 00:10:09,859
the ministerial incumbent
from the administrative minutiae

186
00:10:10,024 --> 00:10:13,061
by devolving
the managerial functions

187
00:10:13,224 --> 00:10:16,694
to those whose qualifications
have betterformed them

188
00:10:16,864 --> 00:10:20,823
forthe performance of such
humble offices, thereby releasing

189
00:10:20,984 --> 00:10:24,294
theirpolitical overlords
forthe more onerous duties

190
00:10:24,464 --> 00:10:27,581
and deliberations which are
the inevitable concomitant

191
00:10:27,744 --> 00:10:29,894
of theirexalted position.

192
00:10:35,424 --> 00:10:38,097
What made you think
I wouldn'twant to hearthat?

193
00:10:38,744 --> 00:10:40,496
I thought it might upset you.

194
00:10:40,784 --> 00:10:43,696
How could it?
I didn't understand a single word.

195
00:10:44,904 --> 00:10:47,976
Foronce in your life,
put it into plain English.

196
00:10:48,144 --> 00:10:49,418
If you insist.

197
00:10:49,624 --> 00:10:52,616
You are not here
to run this Department.

198
00:10:53,104 --> 00:10:54,423
I beg yourpardon?

199
00:10:54,584 --> 00:10:57,018
You are not here
to run this Department.

200
00:10:57,184 --> 00:10:59,493
I think I am.
The people think I am, too.

201
00:10:59,664 --> 00:11:03,179
With respect Minister,
you are... they are wrong.

202
00:11:03,424 --> 00:11:05,335
And who does run
this Department?

203
00:11:05,624 --> 00:11:06,659
I do.

204
00:11:06,824 --> 00:11:08,621
Oh, I see...

205
00:11:08,904 --> 00:11:11,577
- What am I supposed to do?
- We've been through all this.

206
00:11:11,744 --> 00:11:13,223
Make policy.

207
00:11:13,384 --> 00:11:15,022
Get legislation enacted.

208
00:11:15,184 --> 00:11:18,460
And above all secure
the Department's budget in Cabinet.

209
00:11:18,624 --> 00:11:20,933
It seems the budget
is all you care about.

210
00:11:21,104 --> 00:11:22,776
It is rather important.

211
00:11:23,424 --> 00:11:26,063
We might end up
with a department so small

212
00:11:26,224 --> 00:11:28,419
that even a Ministercould run it.

213
00:11:30,464 --> 00:11:33,581
Are we to have a disagreement
about the nature of democracy?

214
00:11:33,744 --> 00:11:36,736
No, Minister, merely
a demarcation dispute.

215
00:11:37,024 --> 00:11:39,902
What I mean
is that the menial chore

216
00:11:40,064 --> 00:11:42,624
of running a department
is beneath you.

217
00:11:43,024 --> 00:11:45,299
You're fashioned
fora noblercalling.

218
00:11:45,544 --> 00:11:48,456
Well, I leave
the routine paperwork to you

219
00:11:48,624 --> 00:11:51,582
but I must insist on direct access
to all information.

220
00:11:51,744 --> 00:11:53,780
Neveragain
"There are some things

221
00:11:53,944 --> 00:11:56,538
it is betterfora Minister
not to know".

222
00:11:56,704 --> 00:11:59,537
- Well, Minister...
- That is an order, Humphrey!

223
00:11:59,744 --> 00:12:03,657
As you say, Minister.
If that is what you really want.

224
00:12:03,824 --> 00:12:07,499
It's treating Cabinet Ministers
as if they were ten yearolds.

225
00:12:16,664 --> 00:12:17,664
Afternoon.

226
00:12:17,824 --> 00:12:19,576
- Finished with The Guardian?
- Yes.

227
00:12:20,944 --> 00:12:23,299
I haven't got
the Socialist Workerforyou.

228
00:12:24,184 --> 00:12:26,937
Daddy's pleased to see you down
forbreakfast?

229
00:12:27,104 --> 00:12:30,016
- He hasn't seen you fora while...
- I was having a lie-in.

230
00:12:30,544 --> 00:12:32,500
Betterthan a sit-in, I suppose.

231
00:12:33,664 --> 00:12:35,495
Why were you so late
last night?

232
00:12:35,744 --> 00:12:39,100
There are some things it's better
fora fathernot to know.

233
00:12:39,504 --> 00:12:40,857
Don't you start!

234
00:12:41,064 --> 00:12:43,453
- What?
- Nothing, nothing.

235
00:12:43,624 --> 00:12:45,455
I was outwith the Trots.

236
00:12:45,984 --> 00:12:47,337
Gosh...

237
00:12:49,664 --> 00:12:51,575
Are you going to see a doctor?

238
00:12:52,624 --> 00:12:54,137
The Trotskyites!

239
00:12:54,704 --> 00:12:56,660
Oh, a Trotskyite now are you?

240
00:12:56,824 --> 00:12:57,973
No. Peter is.

241
00:12:58,144 --> 00:12:59,213
Peter?

242
00:12:59,424 --> 00:13:00,698
Yes, Peter.

243
00:13:01,784 --> 00:13:03,934
You've only met him
about 15 times.

244
00:13:04,104 --> 00:13:06,413
Oh, is he the one with the...
and the...

245
00:13:06,704 --> 00:13:07,704
Yes.

246
